00:05:09.839 --> 00:05:12.519
Are you all, are all three of you in the Boston area?

00:05:12.519 --> 00:05:13.519
Yes.

00:05:13.519 --> 00:05:14.519
Okay, nice.

00:05:14.519 --> 00:05:19.040
Well, I know we kind of alluded to the data jam a little bit.

00:05:19.040 --> 00:05:23.559
So I thought it might be helpful in the beginning to just kind of share a little bit about the

00:05:23.559 --> 00:05:27.320
story of how that came to be and maybe what the data jam is.

00:05:27.320 --> 00:05:29.720
Yeah, Danielle, do you want to give it a shot?

00:05:29.720 --> 00:05:33.399
So the whole reason, the whole, so we have a couple of different community of practices

00:05:33.399 --> 00:05:34.399
at Biogen.

00:05:34.399 --> 00:05:38.720
One of them that Anuj and I lead is the data and analytics and really the whole goal was

00:05:38.720 --> 00:05:43.519
just to get people across Biogen that are passionate about data and analytics together,

00:05:43.519 --> 00:05:47.440
just to learn sort of the different ways that we work across the different groups, find

00:05:47.440 --> 00:05:52.079
areas of opportunity and collaboration as well as network.

00:05:52.079 --> 00:05:58.959
And really the way the data jam came about is things have been pretty, has been pretty

00:05:58.959 --> 00:05:59.959
interesting at work.

00:05:59.959 --> 00:06:04.279
And so we wanted to try to find a way to have a little bit of fun, try to get people together.

00:06:04.279 --> 00:06:07.440
I think Anuj had mentioned she loves getting people together, so do I.

00:06:07.440 --> 00:06:11.839
So we decided why not try to throw together a data jam and something that we thought would

00:06:11.839 --> 00:06:16.320
just be something small and fun, turned out to be something actually very big and really

00:06:16.320 --> 00:06:19.839
showed the passion that people at Biogen has for data.

00:06:19.839 --> 00:06:23.600
I don't know, Dan and Anuj, if you want to add on to that.

00:06:23.600 --> 00:06:25.600
That was pretty good from my perspective.

00:06:25.600 --> 00:06:30.799
I mean, I think, you know, anything that's successful, I think always happens, something

00:06:30.799 --> 00:06:31.799
like this.

00:06:31.799 --> 00:06:35.040
Danielle comes to me, Danielle and Anuj come to me in one meeting and say, hey, I think

00:06:35.040 --> 00:06:36.760
we should like do it like a data competition.

00:06:36.760 --> 00:06:41.640
Like, all right, sure, let's, let's put that together, let's see what that looks like.

00:06:41.640 --> 00:06:48.799
And you know, the day you send it out, like I was hoping, I was hoping myself 30 people

00:06:48.799 --> 00:06:49.799
would show up.

00:06:49.799 --> 00:06:54.679
I thought if we had 30 people, we'd have like, we'd put like five people on a team, you have

00:06:54.679 --> 00:06:58.399
like six teams, you have a good competition with six teams.

00:06:58.399 --> 00:07:03.440
I think in the first hour, 50 people signed up and then we just kind of went into panic

00:07:03.440 --> 00:07:06.920
mode of how we're going to organize this, which we could also talk about because there's

00:07:06.920 --> 00:07:09.079
a lot there.

00:07:09.079 --> 00:07:12.679
But really, you know, I think it, it starts on something small.

00:07:12.679 --> 00:07:16.040
And then you, we just had such a great team together to be able to put something like

00:07:16.040 --> 00:07:17.040
this together.

00:07:17.040 --> 00:07:19.519
Just, it really worked out well.

00:07:19.519 --> 00:07:24.559
I think a lot of people like have ideas for things like this, or just like ideas in general

00:07:24.559 --> 00:07:29.000
that they'll bring to meetings, but you all actually made it happen.

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:34.600
How did you go from just an idea for something to making it this real life event?

00:07:34.600 --> 00:07:37.600
And Nuju, you want to take that?

00:07:37.600 --> 00:07:39.519
Yeah, I can take that.

00:07:39.519 --> 00:07:45.959
I think actually executing to the point of like, send, getting a data set and sending

00:07:45.959 --> 00:07:50.160
out a form for signups was fairly straightforward.

00:07:50.160 --> 00:07:53.640
We had a couple of ideas of data sets that we could use.

00:07:53.640 --> 00:07:57.359
And so we landed on one and then just kind of decided to go for it.

00:07:57.359 --> 00:08:01.440
We had enough information to execute and we sent it out.

00:08:01.440 --> 00:08:06.600
Where the challenge came in was when we saw the rate of signups because people, we realized

00:08:06.600 --> 00:08:11.359
we knew on some level, but we really saw that people love data and are passionate about

00:08:11.359 --> 00:08:17.359
it and want to work on a hackathon of sorts or a data jam of sorts.

00:08:17.359 --> 00:08:23.200
So I will say that we, it got a little challenging when we hit, you know, 200 to 250 because

00:08:23.200 --> 00:08:29.359
our previous kind of plan for how we were going to run it wasn't really going to work

00:08:29.359 --> 00:08:31.160
anymore given the numbers.

00:08:31.160 --> 00:08:33.599
And so there was a lot of kind of planning on the fly.

00:08:33.599 --> 00:08:38.320
So when we saw how many people there were, we kind of decided let's do two rounds instead

00:08:38.320 --> 00:08:39.320
of one.

00:08:39.320 --> 00:08:43.739
And so it was part of the excitement, but it also was part of the challenge of figuring

00:08:43.739 --> 00:08:48.440
out how to accommodate the growing number of participants.

00:08:48.440 --> 00:08:49.799
So yeah.

00:08:49.799 --> 00:08:53.640
I think part of it too was that we actually had support from our leadership to actually

00:08:53.640 --> 00:08:55.400
go forth and do this.

00:08:55.400 --> 00:08:56.880
And that helped a lot.

00:08:56.880 --> 00:09:01.000
I think part of it too was the fact that there has been a lot of eyes just on data in general

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:02.000
for many different reasons.

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:06.799
So I think that also helped, but a lot of it too was us just trying to figure out how

00:09:06.799 --> 00:09:08.419
to even pull it off.

00:09:08.419 --> 00:09:12.440
And then we did, to be completely honest.

00:09:12.440 --> 00:09:15.400
And you know, I might clarify what Danielle says, because it's not like we were given

00:09:15.400 --> 00:09:18.400
a task to go run a data jam.

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:21.280
Like at some point we just had to make a decision.

00:09:21.280 --> 00:09:23.359
Like Rachel says, there are ideas all the time, right?

00:09:23.359 --> 00:09:26.640
How do you like do it?

00:09:26.640 --> 00:09:28.520
There's a little bit of a leap of faith there.

00:09:28.520 --> 00:09:32.559
I think you just kind of, you know, what's the worst that can happen is no one signs

00:09:32.559 --> 00:09:35.479
up and we just go back to our day jobs.

00:09:35.479 --> 00:09:38.280
What's the best thing that can happen is, you know, a whole bunch of people sign up.

00:09:38.280 --> 00:09:43.840
So there is like just a little bit of boldness from this team to be able to say, all right,

00:09:43.840 --> 00:09:44.840
let's do it.

00:09:44.840 --> 00:09:46.919
Let's give it a shot and see what happens.

00:09:46.919 --> 00:09:51.159
I think a lot of it too is we just asked, like it was like, there's no, there's no downside

00:09:51.159 --> 00:09:52.840
they could, you know, expect, you know?

00:09:52.840 --> 00:09:56.520
And so I think a lot of it was just, we just asked and it seemed like we were able to get

00:09:56.520 --> 00:09:59.200
a lot of things, a lot of yeses actually.

00:09:59.200 --> 00:10:00.200
That's great.

00:10:00.200 --> 00:10:07.119
I've, I've been thinking about doing something kind of like that at Posit so that we could

00:10:07.119 --> 00:10:11.520
like mix people across all different teams, like customer success and some of the open

00:10:11.520 --> 00:10:17.760
source package developers that kind of work on a common problem together.

00:10:17.760 --> 00:10:19.960
And it's just been like an idea floating around in my head.

00:10:19.960 --> 00:10:25.559
So I was just curious how you went and, and made it actually happen.

00:10:25.559 --> 00:10:31.580
But I was wondering for the teams, were people like mixed across different parts of the company

00:10:31.580 --> 00:10:36.599
or could people be, it could be a group of whoever wanted to join together.

00:10:36.599 --> 00:10:38.200
We decided to randomize it.

00:10:38.200 --> 00:10:43.880
And so we had people sign up and part of the signup was asking what their kind of capabilities

00:10:43.880 --> 00:10:44.880
were.

00:10:44.880 --> 00:10:47.400
So is it that they've never really coded before?

00:10:47.400 --> 00:10:50.559
Are they like experts or gurus?

00:10:50.559 --> 00:10:53.200
Do they fall somewhere in the middle?

00:10:53.200 --> 00:11:02.239
So we, we kind of defined four different levels of competency and had people describe or kind

00:11:02.239 --> 00:11:05.419
of self identify within one of those four.

00:11:05.419 --> 00:11:09.739
And then what we tried to do is when we did randomize teams, we tried to kind of spread

00:11:09.739 --> 00:11:11.020
the capabilities out.

00:11:11.020 --> 00:11:15.900
Honestly, most people fell in the middle, but we didn't want to put all the experts

00:11:15.900 --> 00:11:19.700
together, but also didn't want to have a team that was all novices.

00:11:19.700 --> 00:11:24.500
And so we, the data jam, of course it was about data, but another kind of primary element

00:11:24.500 --> 00:11:26.500
was for people to meet each other.

00:11:26.500 --> 00:11:29.340
And so we didn't want people to just stay within their teams.

00:11:29.340 --> 00:11:31.900
So this was an opportunity to network outside as well.

00:11:31.900 --> 00:11:32.900
Yeah.

00:11:33.380 --> 00:11:34.380
It was kind of wild.

00:11:34.380 --> 00:11:39.020
The teams, because we don't know any of the people, you know, but Biogen's a big company,

00:11:39.020 --> 00:11:44.059
but the teams end up kind of wild, you know, multiple time zones, people in like Buenos

00:11:44.059 --> 00:11:49.940
Aires and China and Switzerland and US and you know, they gave them like three weeks

00:11:49.940 --> 00:11:51.299
to go analyze some data.

00:11:51.299 --> 00:11:52.340
They don't know each other.

00:11:52.340 --> 00:11:56.900
They're working wildly different departments, you know, some in manufacturing, some in sales,

00:11:56.900 --> 00:11:59.500
you know, some in R&D.

00:11:59.500 --> 00:12:05.859
So like you're saying, Rachel, a big part is getting those people, force them into something.

00:12:05.859 --> 00:12:12.299
And I feel like you get a lot of benefit when people are forced to problem solve together

00:12:12.299 --> 00:12:18.140
because that like, it creates like a little bit of, I don't know, a little bit of conflict.

00:12:18.140 --> 00:12:21.659
And when you get that conflict, then you get people's different opinions coming out and

00:12:21.659 --> 00:12:24.380
the different viewpoints, then you build on something together.

00:12:24.380 --> 00:12:29.820
So I think that part was really wildly successful and people had a good time meeting people

00:12:29.820 --> 00:12:30.820
across the org.

00:12:30.820 --> 00:12:31.820
Thank you.

00:12:31.820 --> 00:12:34.859
Alan, I see you asked a question in the chat here.

00:12:34.859 --> 00:12:35.859
Do you want to jump in?

00:12:35.859 --> 00:12:36.859
Yeah, sure.

00:12:36.859 --> 00:12:37.859
Hey, everybody.

00:12:37.859 --> 00:12:42.780
Um, I think Dan was kind of just speaking to part of the question, noting that folks

00:12:42.780 --> 00:12:45.539
had sort of several weeks to put something together and they were kind of all over the

00:12:45.539 --> 00:12:46.539
place.

00:12:46.539 --> 00:12:49.539
I'd really like to know more about like, what did they, what did they make?

00:12:49.539 --> 00:12:52.780
Like, and how much structure did you give them to lead into that?

00:12:52.780 --> 00:12:55.900
Like, was this a, an internal and external data set?

00:12:55.900 --> 00:12:59.419
And did you give them a bunch of specific problems or did you say, Hey, here's a pile

00:12:59.419 --> 00:13:02.820
of data, like find something fun and interesting and make something.

00:13:02.820 --> 00:13:07.299
And I'm just curious about the array of things that they made and what the, like sharing

00:13:07.299 --> 00:13:12.460
with a great big set of like 200 people sharing that back out at scale is also really challenging.

00:13:12.460 --> 00:13:16.780
So, you know, how did that, um, how did the sort of conducting of the rest of the thing

00:13:16.780 --> 00:13:17.780
kind of unfold?

00:13:17.780 --> 00:13:19.700
Um, there's a whole bunch there.

00:13:19.700 --> 00:13:21.179
I think Dan's number is kind of interesting to speak to.

00:13:21.179 --> 00:13:23.780
Um, I'd love to hear about, thanks.

00:13:23.780 --> 00:13:24.780
Maybe Danielle.

00:13:24.780 --> 00:13:25.780
Yeah.

00:13:25.780 --> 00:13:29.179
So we actually, um, so we started with an internal data set.

00:13:29.179 --> 00:13:33.059
It was a survey that was done a few years ago, specifically around, um, data maturity

00:13:33.059 --> 00:13:34.059
at Biogen.

00:13:34.059 --> 00:13:40.500
Um, and so we had a data set, um, that was kind of easy, somewhat easy to use and understand.

00:13:40.500 --> 00:13:46.500
Um, and then the way we set it up was we gave the teams, um, a few weeks to, uh, analyze

00:13:46.500 --> 00:13:50.820
the data set in whatever fashion or whatever type of tool they wanted to use.

00:13:50.820 --> 00:13:54.099
Um, and the idea was to generate insights.

00:13:54.099 --> 00:13:57.580
Um, there were a few key questions that we had asked, but other than that, it was pretty

00:13:57.580 --> 00:13:58.580
much open.

00:13:58.580 --> 00:14:01.580
Um, and then present it not in PowerPoint.

00:14:01.580 --> 00:14:04.859
So the challenge here was to not use PowerPoint and to be creative.

00:14:04.859 --> 00:14:13.140
Um, and so what we did was we had a few rounds of, um, uh, sort of battle rounds, like kind

00:14:13.140 --> 00:14:18.380
of posed it as like a Eurovision, the voice type of, you know, head to head, knockout

00:14:18.380 --> 00:14:22.659
battle rounds where we had groups of, I think it was five or six teams.

00:14:22.659 --> 00:14:26.460
Um, and then they would vote for the one team to move forward to the finale.

00:14:26.460 --> 00:14:33.940
So at the end we had, uh, I think 22 teams down to five teams, the five teams, yeah.

00:14:33.940 --> 00:14:39.219
Four or five, you know, I know it's kind of a blurred out, but we had it down to five

00:14:39.219 --> 00:14:40.219
teams.

00:14:40.299 --> 00:14:45.219
Um, after that we had like the big finale where it was, um, something that we did in

00:14:45.219 --> 00:14:48.460
our, one of our auditoriums and we had all the teams come present.

00:14:48.460 --> 00:14:52.739
We were actually able to get our executive, some executive committee members to come and

00:14:52.739 --> 00:14:54.659
do some openings and some closing.

00:14:54.659 --> 00:14:56.260
And we had got our CEO there.

00:14:56.260 --> 00:15:02.219
It was a really big event where, um, we then had people present in a shark, uh, tank style

00:15:02.219 --> 00:15:07.979
pitch about, uh, the data sets and, um, sort of what they would recommend to, um, better,

00:15:07.979 --> 00:15:12.020
um, to have better data stewardship, um, and different types of strategies with data

00:15:12.020 --> 00:15:13.380
at Biogen.

00:15:13.380 --> 00:15:18.140
And then we crowned a winner at the end, we had some trophies and medals.

00:15:18.140 --> 00:15:23.140
I love how you're mixing all these reality shows, like The Voice and Shark Tank.

00:15:23.140 --> 00:15:29.500
And I, um, I see Jesse asked a question in the chat and I see a star there, so I'll read

00:15:29.500 --> 00:15:30.500
it.

00:15:30.500 --> 00:15:34.619
But the question was, um, did the competition happen during work hours?

00:15:34.619 --> 00:15:38.619
And if so, how did you pitch the idea to leadership to get them on board?

00:15:38.619 --> 00:15:43.619
I know you just mentioned like the CEO was there for the beginning of the competition.

00:15:43.619 --> 00:15:48.619
Um, what did you appeal to in order to get them to buy into the idea?

00:15:48.619 --> 00:15:49.619
Yes.

00:15:49.619 --> 00:15:51.619
Um, we didn't ask.

00:15:51.619 --> 00:15:55.900
Um, you know, we, uh, we threw it out there.

00:15:55.900 --> 00:15:59.020
We threw it out there and said, you know, I saw another question about, did we start

00:15:59.020 --> 00:16:01.260
with a problem and have people solve the problem?

00:16:01.260 --> 00:16:03.659
We just threw a data set out there and said, look, find some insights.

00:16:03.700 --> 00:16:04.700
We left it really broad.

00:16:04.700 --> 00:16:08.539
People came back and said, well, how much time should I spend on this?

00:16:08.539 --> 00:16:11.900
And of course, data scientists could go nuts on something like this.

00:16:11.900 --> 00:16:16.820
So we've tried to like, you know, look, you only have three total weeks to work on this

00:16:16.820 --> 00:16:17.820
thing.

00:16:17.820 --> 00:16:21.299
Um, and you have a big, broad team and everything.

00:16:21.299 --> 00:16:27.020
So, uh, for, for the question that was just posed, we didn't ask leadership.

00:16:27.020 --> 00:16:34.619
We asked people to volunteer, um, and, you know, just kind of try to keep it manageable.

00:16:34.619 --> 00:16:38.820
I think, I forget what we said, total number of hours over the three weeks, maybe around

00:16:38.820 --> 00:16:39.820
like eight.

00:16:39.820 --> 00:16:41.820
I think we said it was up to their discretion.

00:16:41.820 --> 00:16:43.099
It's up to their discretion.

00:16:43.099 --> 00:16:46.380
Some did a lot, but some did not so much.

00:16:46.380 --> 00:16:48.979
I think part of it too was, I mean, there was support for this.

00:16:48.979 --> 00:16:52.700
I think, you know, we've been going through a lot of changes and again, there was a lot

00:16:52.700 --> 00:16:53.700
of focus on data.

00:16:53.700 --> 00:16:55.820
So part of this too was a culture piece.

00:16:55.820 --> 00:17:00.979
And I think the recognition that this is a vital part of, you know, working at a company

00:17:00.979 --> 00:17:02.780
is the, the culture and the experience.

00:17:02.780 --> 00:17:08.500
So I think a lot of that, um, also allowed for this to happen and not really need permission

00:17:08.500 --> 00:17:09.500
per se.

00:17:09.500 --> 00:17:16.699
I see Ted commented about the data governance piece being so important and maybe this chips

00:17:16.699 --> 00:17:22.219
a little bit away from the data jam, but like, what are some things you've learned about

00:17:22.219 --> 00:17:24.699
data governance through this or before?

00:17:24.699 --> 00:17:26.260
Yeah, this is a good one.

00:17:26.260 --> 00:17:27.260
I can take this.

00:17:27.260 --> 00:17:30.660
Um, you know, my, my role here is around data stewardship.

00:17:30.660 --> 00:17:36.140
I mean, people talk about data governance, but personally, everyone hates data governance

00:17:36.140 --> 00:17:42.060
across the board, executives, everyone, but so I rebranded it into data stewardship, which

00:17:42.060 --> 00:17:46.739
I think evokes a little bit more of we're all in this together and we do our own stewardship

00:17:46.739 --> 00:17:48.739
of the, of the information.

00:17:48.739 --> 00:17:52.380
So what we, what we ask people to do, and I'm going to get it wrong, what we asked,

00:17:52.380 --> 00:17:57.339
but we asked for like an insight and we asked for a data stewardship recommendation and we

00:17:57.339 --> 00:18:01.979
asked for one other thing, but I forget what that was now.

00:18:01.979 --> 00:18:05.900
But you know, we got a lot of stuff and then the, the survey itself was about how well

00:18:05.900 --> 00:18:10.900
does Biogen steward data and how well do we leverage data?

00:18:10.900 --> 00:18:14.619
So all of the questions in the survey were about this and then the topic was about this

00:18:14.619 --> 00:18:15.619
too.

00:18:15.619 --> 00:18:20.219
Um, you know, so like what we heard was probably not surprising to a lot of people, but data

00:18:20.219 --> 00:18:21.219
is hard to find.

00:18:21.219 --> 00:18:24.459
It's hard to get access to data.

00:18:24.459 --> 00:18:27.939
And then we had a lot of great recommendations on how we could improve that.

00:18:27.939 --> 00:18:29.939
Manuja, did I miss anything?

00:18:29.939 --> 00:18:36.180
I know you, you covered it pretty well, but I think in addition to that, the fact that

00:18:36.180 --> 00:18:42.660
I would say 80 to 90% of the teams, which were incredibly cross-functional came to the

00:18:42.660 --> 00:18:46.619
same conclusion, which was that data is hard to find and access.

00:18:46.619 --> 00:18:52.979
And so it's not a problem that's kind of isolated to a single group.

00:18:52.979 --> 00:18:58.459
It's pretty, pretty functional, cross-functional, which I thought was fascinating.

00:18:58.459 --> 00:19:02.260
It was expected, but it was still like very interesting to actually see it.

00:19:02.260 --> 00:19:06.060
I think part of it too generated a lot of ideas on how to make it better.

00:19:06.060 --> 00:19:10.500
And so that was some of the pitches had sort of geared their, their thoughts and their

00:19:10.500 --> 00:19:11.500
pitch around.

00:19:11.500 --> 00:19:12.500
Okay.

00:19:12.500 --> 00:19:15.699
Yeah, this is what it is, but these are some of the ways that we could work to, to improve

00:19:15.699 --> 00:19:16.699
it.

00:19:16.699 --> 00:19:19.459
I'd love to hear some of those ways to improve it.

00:19:19.459 --> 00:19:23.979
Cause I'm sure a lot of us are facing, facing that too, if that's something you can share.

00:19:23.979 --> 00:19:30.219
I know there was a lot around kind of metadata driven cataloging, ensuring that, you know,

00:19:30.219 --> 00:19:31.900
your data isn't all over the place.

00:19:31.900 --> 00:19:38.380
There was a lot of conversation about the fact that, you know, copying data is something

00:19:38.380 --> 00:19:42.900
that happens on occasion is, and is obviously not best practice.

00:19:42.900 --> 00:19:52.500
So I think the big ones that we saw were essentially a catalog to understand what data even exists.

00:19:52.500 --> 00:19:57.420
So that, you know, we know what's there and then find a way for people who need to access

00:19:57.420 --> 00:20:00.099
it to be able to access it.

00:20:00.099 --> 00:20:02.619
So that was a, that was a big one that we saw.

00:20:02.619 --> 00:20:06.619
And the other piece really was actually having the enterprise wide strategy.

00:20:06.619 --> 00:20:10.859
I think that was one of the key things that was, you know, identified was just needing

00:20:10.859 --> 00:20:15.219
some sort of consistent across enterprise and not just specific to each of the different

00:20:15.219 --> 00:20:16.219
individual functions.

00:20:16.219 --> 00:20:18.979
I'm trying to think back to, this was in May.

00:20:18.979 --> 00:20:25.979
So it was a little bit ago, but one of the ones that resonated with me was, you know,

00:20:25.979 --> 00:20:32.420
not to kind of create like a partial catalog or something like that, where as soon as you

00:20:32.420 --> 00:20:37.140
create it, it's out of date and then end up being another stale data asset that you

00:20:37.140 --> 00:20:38.420
have.

00:20:38.420 --> 00:20:43.979
So really trying to weigh, like Danielle was saying, to enterprise it or productionalize

00:20:43.979 --> 00:20:48.380
it and then find ways to make sure that it's, it's sustainable long-term, because I feel

00:20:48.380 --> 00:20:53.500
like that's where we, where we always end up with a hiccup of like, how do we, we could

00:20:53.500 --> 00:20:59.819
get it going, but then how do we actually keep it going?

00:20:59.819 --> 00:21:06.699
Is that your team that's responsible for enterprise data strategy, or I'm trying to

00:21:06.699 --> 00:21:11.219
remember the name of the group, technology strategy and innovation, or is that another

00:21:11.219 --> 00:21:12.219
company?

00:21:12.219 --> 00:21:17.219
No, mine's like, the piece that I'm in charge of is the clinical trial data.

00:21:17.219 --> 00:21:22.819
But so obviously at Biogen, there's more data than that, but the enterprise, it's kind of

00:21:22.819 --> 00:21:27.939
just across all the individual functions, they do probably similar to what it looks

00:21:27.939 --> 00:21:31.780
like at Posit, probably similar to what it looks like at everyone else's company.

00:21:31.780 --> 00:21:32.780
Yeah.

00:21:32.780 --> 00:21:39.339
There was an anonymous question that was from a technology perspective, how did teams interact

00:21:39.339 --> 00:21:40.579
on the data jam?

00:21:40.579 --> 00:21:42.099
Did they use common tools?

00:21:42.099 --> 00:21:51.339
There was a variety, and I think it, the randomization of teams kind of spoke to what tools ended

00:21:51.339 --> 00:21:52.339
up being used.

00:21:52.339 --> 00:21:57.920
So for instance, I, we obviously didn't interact with every single team, but what ended up

00:21:57.920 --> 00:22:04.920
happening was there was a kind of data communication person, a person in charge of creating the

00:22:04.920 --> 00:22:10.959
output, a person who was more of the programmer, and then the person who was kind of describing

00:22:10.959 --> 00:22:14.040
what the approach would be to actually solving the problem.

00:22:14.040 --> 00:22:19.199
So it really depended on what programming tools that people within that specific team

00:22:19.199 --> 00:22:24.199
were most comfortable with, which kind of made it more exciting because we had people

00:22:24.199 --> 00:22:29.439
working in R, people working in SAS, people working in Power BI, amongst others.

00:22:29.439 --> 00:22:38.000
And so folks did rely a lot on what we had in-house just because it's kind of, you know,

00:22:38.000 --> 00:22:39.000
sensitive data.

00:22:39.000 --> 00:22:44.160
So we didn't want to kind of put it on external tools, but there was still quite a variety

00:22:44.160 --> 00:22:50.079
of what was used to produce the end results and the solutions.

00:22:50.079 --> 00:22:52.079
Thank you.

00:22:52.959 --> 00:22:58.199
George, I see you had a question in the chat just now, but maybe also one from earlier.

00:22:58.199 --> 00:23:00.199
So feel free to ask both there.

00:23:00.199 --> 00:23:01.199
Thanks.

00:23:01.199 --> 00:23:07.719
Yeah, I was wondering if you've obtained any feedback from the participants on, you know,

00:23:07.719 --> 00:23:14.880
the different aspects, like the technology side, what it's like, especially, you know,

00:23:14.880 --> 00:23:19.160
they may not really interact with a lot because, you know, cross-functional.

00:23:19.239 --> 00:23:21.239
Neutra, Danielle, do you want to take that?

00:23:21.239 --> 00:23:24.839
Yeah, so we did actually do a post-event survey.

00:23:24.839 --> 00:23:31.239
So a lot of it was just understanding, you know, thoughts and feedback on the format.

00:23:31.239 --> 00:23:32.839
Would they participate in something like this again?

00:23:32.839 --> 00:23:36.680
I think at the end of the day, there was a lot of really positive feedback on the actual

00:23:36.680 --> 00:23:38.920
data jam and wanting to do it again.

00:23:38.920 --> 00:23:43.079
And there are just obviously some logistical things that we had to deal with that we could

00:23:43.079 --> 00:23:44.880
always make better for next time.

00:23:44.880 --> 00:23:49.439
I think one of the challenges was the different geographic location.

00:23:49.439 --> 00:23:53.560
I think that was tough trying to find, you know, teams that were kind of spread across

00:23:53.560 --> 00:23:55.959
when they could actually meet because of the different time zones.

00:23:55.959 --> 00:24:00.880
So there are a lot of things that we have sort of on our list to think about for Data

00:24:00.880 --> 00:24:01.880
Jam 2.0.

00:24:01.880 --> 00:24:07.040
But at the end, we did get a lot of positive feedback and a lot of good ideas for the next

00:24:07.040 --> 00:24:08.040
one.

00:24:08.040 --> 00:24:11.040
And Anuja, Dan, anything to add?

00:24:11.199 --> 00:24:12.199
No, I don't.

00:24:12.199 --> 00:24:18.719
I actually don't think we got too much feedback in the way of the usage of tools.

00:24:18.719 --> 00:24:23.040
The technology piece actually, it seemed to work pretty well, depending on what people

00:24:23.040 --> 00:24:24.040
wanted to use.

00:24:24.040 --> 00:24:26.319
To Danielle's point, it was more logistics.

00:24:26.319 --> 00:24:30.000
And then there was also feedback around the type of data set that we could potentially

00:24:30.000 --> 00:24:32.760
use for upcoming data jams.

00:24:32.760 --> 00:24:38.400
So for instance, for this one, we did surveys and some people love analyzing survey data.

00:24:38.400 --> 00:24:39.599
Some people despise it.

00:24:39.599 --> 00:24:44.680
So there was some feedback there around, you know, what else can we do moving forward

00:24:44.680 --> 00:24:46.680
and what data sets could we use?

00:24:46.680 --> 00:24:48.520
I think that was another good point.

00:24:48.520 --> 00:24:51.000
A lot of people had offered like, hey, we're going to do this again.

00:24:51.000 --> 00:24:52.000
Can you please use our data?

00:24:52.000 --> 00:24:54.000
So that was pretty cool, too.

00:24:54.000 --> 00:25:02.079
Yeah, that's exciting, getting people thinking about, hey, I want to use my data for this.

00:25:02.079 --> 00:25:05.760
I see that there are a few questions in the chat here, too.

00:25:05.760 --> 00:25:11.520
I think, Kevin, you asked one about different formats that people use.

00:25:11.520 --> 00:25:12.520
Sure.

00:25:12.520 --> 00:25:13.520
Yeah.

00:25:13.520 --> 00:25:21.119
Yeah, I like that idea of forcing them not to use PowerPoint because I definitely find

00:25:21.119 --> 00:25:22.119
PowerPoint presentations.

00:25:22.119 --> 00:25:27.959
I definitely learn less from PowerPoint presentations than any other format, I think, that exists.

00:25:27.959 --> 00:25:31.880
But I'm curious, like, what other formats people ended up using, you know, instead of

00:25:31.880 --> 00:25:32.880
PowerPoint.

00:25:33.000 --> 00:25:37.119
Some people use the Power BI dashboards directly and went through that.

00:25:37.119 --> 00:25:40.520
Others use some forms of, like, Canva or animations.

00:25:40.520 --> 00:25:45.040
There was one really cool group that did sort of these animations to tell their story.

00:25:45.040 --> 00:25:46.040
Anything?

00:25:46.040 --> 00:25:50.000
I know, so a lot of Power BI, Canva, animations.

00:25:50.000 --> 00:25:53.000
There were a couple of shiny applications.

00:25:53.000 --> 00:25:55.000
Oh, there you go.

00:25:55.000 --> 00:25:56.000
Yeah.

00:25:56.000 --> 00:25:57.000
Go ahead.

00:25:57.000 --> 00:26:01.239
So when you put this question out there, you never know what you're going to get, right?

00:26:01.239 --> 00:26:02.719
You have to come back.

00:26:03.560 --> 00:26:05.760
It has to be a presentation under five minutes, I think.

00:26:05.760 --> 00:26:06.760
Yeah.

00:26:06.760 --> 00:26:07.760
Five minutes.

00:26:07.760 --> 00:26:08.760
It has to explain, like, these three things.

00:26:08.760 --> 00:26:11.760
So what are we going to get?

00:26:11.760 --> 00:26:12.760
Kind of unbelievable.

00:26:12.760 --> 00:26:16.479
I mean, we had people, like, dressing up in costumes.

00:26:16.479 --> 00:26:21.520
We had, like, we had people do, like, a set of, like, trivia questions.

00:26:21.520 --> 00:26:24.040
Oh, I like the Kahoot.

00:26:24.040 --> 00:26:31.439
And then we definitely had some animation, like, to tell the whole story.

00:26:31.439 --> 00:26:36.239
People walking through the Power BI dashboard, people walking through shiny apps, stuff like

00:26:36.239 --> 00:26:37.239
that.

00:26:37.239 --> 00:26:38.239
But, you know, some really interesting stuff.

00:26:38.239 --> 00:26:42.479
And I think people had fun with it, even if they didn't have, like, a big, you know, epiphany

00:26:42.479 --> 00:26:44.199
of data science in this.

00:26:44.199 --> 00:26:48.880
But they were just able to present something, because we know that you need a lot of skills

00:26:48.880 --> 00:26:49.880
for data science, right?

00:26:49.880 --> 00:26:55.800
And so part of the storytelling and everything is part of it, too, getting the message across.

00:26:55.800 --> 00:26:59.160
Which formats do you think were most effective?

00:26:59.160 --> 00:27:05.280
I would say the funnier, the better, personally, for this one.

00:27:05.280 --> 00:27:08.319
But I think it really depends on what you're, what message you're trying to convey.

00:27:08.319 --> 00:27:12.680
I mean, if you're really, I think we have some people who did some really deep statistical

00:27:12.680 --> 00:27:17.719
analyses, and they had shiny apps up, and I think that was really helpful to do that

00:27:17.719 --> 00:27:18.719
stuff.

00:27:18.719 --> 00:27:24.719
But for, like, the big, broad 300-person audience, I think you want to go big and go creative.

00:27:25.719 --> 00:27:29.680
Yeah, I think when we think about the finale, there were a lot of, there were a few that

00:27:29.680 --> 00:27:32.119
were Power BI, but they didn't just do Power BI.

00:27:32.119 --> 00:27:37.040
They had sort of some animations, or the way they had presented it was a little bit on

00:27:37.040 --> 00:27:38.560
the more creative side.

00:27:38.560 --> 00:27:47.800
Yeah, I like this idea of, like, just making it accessible to whatever tools people wanted

00:27:47.800 --> 00:27:53.239
to use, like, if they wanted to present it in Canva, which is a tool I love for doing

00:27:53.280 --> 00:27:57.319
design, too, that they could use whatever they wanted.

00:27:58.560 --> 00:28:05.880
Yeah, and I feel like, oh, sorry, Dan, I was just going to say, it was less about the output,

00:28:05.880 --> 00:28:11.439
like one type of output being more effective than the other, but more so about how you

00:28:11.439 --> 00:28:16.319
communicated what you were trying to get at, how you communicated your story.

00:28:16.319 --> 00:28:21.959
So I feel like I saw effective presentations across all formats.

00:28:22.599 --> 00:28:26.000
And I was just going to say, we're trying to make it as inclusive as possible.

00:28:26.000 --> 00:28:30.920
So it's not, you know, only for PhD statisticians, of which we have a lot here.

00:28:31.880 --> 00:28:36.640
It's like, really, you know, it could be a novice, have no idea anything about data,

00:28:36.640 --> 00:28:40.959
but you'd be maybe more creative for the presentation side, and you could, like, hear

00:28:40.959 --> 00:28:45.119
from them. So, you know, a lot of, like, cross-pollination with different people and

00:28:45.119 --> 00:28:48.319
really keeping it open, use whatever you want, do whatever you want.

00:28:49.199 --> 00:28:53.400
Yeah, and I think the teams also really leveraged the skill sets and the strengths of

00:28:53.400 --> 00:28:56.640
each member on their team. So some of the people were more heavy in the background, and

00:28:56.640 --> 00:28:59.839
some of the other people were more front and center in terms of presentation.

00:28:59.839 --> 00:29:03.000
So I think a lot of teams use that to their advantage as well.

00:29:05.239 --> 00:29:07.040
That's really cool. Thanks for sharing that.

00:29:08.479 --> 00:29:10.880
George, you'd like a follow up on that kind of?

00:29:11.839 --> 00:29:18.920
Yeah, actually, I was wondering, you know, if any of those creative formats have become

00:29:18.920 --> 00:29:23.199
normalized in the culture, you know, because that's, it seems like such a variety.

00:29:23.199 --> 00:29:27.479
I mean, I don't expect someone to just, like, constantly, you know, dance, do an

00:29:27.479 --> 00:29:32.319
interpretive dance to their presentations, but something along the lines of, you know, a

00:29:32.319 --> 00:29:35.199
little bit more creativity and going beyond the PowerPoint.

00:29:36.079 --> 00:29:38.560
Does any of those, have any of those become like a mainstay?

00:29:38.680 --> 00:29:43.359
I mean, speaking personally, now, when I try to do something, I think about what can I use

00:29:43.359 --> 00:29:46.520
other than PowerPoint? I don't know if that's necessarily across the board, but it's

00:29:46.520 --> 00:29:50.599
definitely something that I keep in mind anytime I'm trying to present some sort of

00:29:50.599 --> 00:29:54.479
visualization or insights is just trying to be a little bit more creative.

00:29:55.599 --> 00:29:59.280
Yeah, I think we definitely got some feedback saying, oh, I'm going to read, I have to

00:29:59.280 --> 00:30:02.079
rethink about how I've been presenting in analytics results.

00:30:03.000 --> 00:30:05.520
And our CEO is definitely anti PowerPoint, too.

00:30:05.520 --> 00:30:12.319
So, you know, he likes the idea of information being communicated in some other way that's

00:30:12.319 --> 00:30:16.839
more like other people are saying here, it's more accessible, more easier to to interpret.

00:30:18.359 --> 00:30:20.160
I'm feeling bad for PowerPoint right now.

00:30:20.160 --> 00:30:22.000
Some PowerPoints are beautiful, too.

00:30:24.479 --> 00:30:27.000
I see, Alan, you had a question a little bit earlier.

00:30:27.000 --> 00:30:27.920
Do you want to jump in here?

00:30:29.199 --> 00:30:33.520
Yeah, sure. I was curious if there were insights or things in particular that you

00:30:33.560 --> 00:30:37.760
were curious if there were insights or things in particular from what people produce that

00:30:37.760 --> 00:30:43.199
could be pulled back by the like the owners of the data to turn into anything that becomes

00:30:43.199 --> 00:30:47.400
programmatic or insights that they can then act on like that obviously would be a great

00:30:47.400 --> 00:30:54.079
outcome. Like, hey, we get 100, 200 people together and it's a great engaging activity.

00:30:54.079 --> 00:30:58.239
And it's super cool if the team that owns that data could say, hey, you found a bunch

00:30:58.239 --> 00:31:02.160
of stuff for you. You started some ideas that we can capitalize on and take forward.

00:31:03.119 --> 00:31:04.719
Were they able to take anything like that away?

00:31:06.160 --> 00:31:07.439
We'll let you, Dan, speak about it.

00:31:10.479 --> 00:31:18.160
So I think a lot of data jams go with this idea of like, here's this data set or maybe

00:31:18.160 --> 00:31:20.319
like Kaggles like this, right? Here's this data set.

00:31:20.319 --> 00:31:21.760
Figure out this thing for me.

00:31:21.760 --> 00:31:23.599
And ours wasn't exactly like that.

00:31:23.599 --> 00:31:26.319
So we didn't know exactly what might come out of it.

00:31:26.319 --> 00:31:30.319
But I can tell you what came out of it, at least from my perspective.

00:31:30.400 --> 00:31:34.239
I know a lot of people reached out to some of the people who were either Shiny developers

00:31:34.239 --> 00:31:38.400
or Power BI to get consults on how to do stuff.

00:31:40.239 --> 00:31:46.400
Our CEO reached out to us and asked, how do we fix this whole data problem that we have

00:31:46.400 --> 00:31:49.920
at Biogen that he just heard for two hours during the data jam?

00:31:51.920 --> 00:31:53.680
And I had one more, but then I lost it.

00:31:54.079 --> 00:32:01.040
Oh, and one of the metadata catalogs that someone recommended, they called it DASH.

00:32:01.040 --> 00:32:02.000
I forget what it stands for.

00:32:03.520 --> 00:32:06.079
But it was like an idea of just a metadata catalog.

00:32:06.079 --> 00:32:11.280
And that's being taken up by our computational biology in research.

00:32:11.280 --> 00:32:13.520
And they're going to try to push that forward next year.

00:32:14.479 --> 00:32:20.319
Maybe this isn't something you can necessarily put a number around, but have you seen that

00:32:20.319 --> 00:32:26.640
have you seen that people are working better cross-functionally because of the data jam?

00:32:30.079 --> 00:32:31.280
Biogen is a big company.

00:32:32.560 --> 00:32:36.160
I think we have about 7,000 employees worldwide.

00:32:36.160 --> 00:32:41.119
So I don't know that we can really get a pure KPI on that one.

00:32:42.160 --> 00:32:48.319
But I think you definitely hear of some interactions that never would have taken place before.

00:32:48.880 --> 00:32:53.599
And I think we run these two community of practices, which I think are kind of like this,

00:32:53.599 --> 00:32:56.239
where you get people who are passionate about something together.

00:32:56.239 --> 00:32:58.880
You have them talk about different topics.

00:32:58.880 --> 00:33:02.400
We have one around data stewardship that I run and one about

00:33:04.880 --> 00:33:08.640
Biogen analytics and data community of practice, which they call BADCOP,

00:33:09.439 --> 00:33:11.280
which Danielle and Anuja run.

00:33:12.000 --> 00:33:15.920
But we've definitely had more people volunteer for leadership in there.

00:33:15.920 --> 00:33:20.160
And we're getting their voices in to continue this conversation.

00:33:20.880 --> 00:33:24.079
I mean, I can say, too, that I've gotten a lot of feedback on,

00:33:24.079 --> 00:33:25.680
oh, thank you so much for having this.

00:33:25.680 --> 00:33:27.680
I was able to connect with this person.

00:33:27.680 --> 00:33:31.599
And I was able to solve whatever issue or whatever problem where I was able to get

00:33:31.599 --> 00:33:32.959
extra help on this.

00:33:32.959 --> 00:33:38.400
So there has been a lot of connections made that then help somebody in their

00:33:38.400 --> 00:33:39.760
current role or responsibility.

00:33:40.959 --> 00:33:41.439
That's great.

00:33:42.400 --> 00:33:47.280
OK, Kevin, with the hard question in the chat, do you want to jump in here, Kevin?

00:33:47.280 --> 00:33:50.160
So your CEO asked you, how do you fix the whole data problem?

00:33:50.160 --> 00:33:54.319
I'm just curious, what did you say or what are you planning on getting back to him with

00:33:54.319 --> 00:33:55.520
an answer for that question?

00:33:55.520 --> 00:33:57.040
That's a big question.

00:33:57.920 --> 00:33:58.800
It was a big question.

00:33:58.800 --> 00:34:02.400
And we were kind of like, oh, OK, yeah, we'll come back to you.

00:34:03.439 --> 00:34:04.719
We thought about it for a long time.

00:34:06.319 --> 00:34:10.719
And I think we've seen, I'm sure you've seen, I'm not sure what organization you're in,

00:34:10.800 --> 00:34:16.800
but like a lot of these initiatives come and go and a lot of hype about, you know,

00:34:16.800 --> 00:34:20.800
fix the world through data or fix the entire business through data.

00:34:20.800 --> 00:34:25.439
So we talked about this a lot, Danielle, Anuja, myself, Sam.

00:34:26.719 --> 00:34:31.840
And the idea, everyone wants the answer to this.

00:34:31.840 --> 00:34:35.360
OK, well, the answer is it's complicated.

00:34:36.159 --> 00:34:42.639
But I think the answer that we really need to do is where do we want to be as an organization

00:34:42.639 --> 00:34:43.199
with data?

00:34:44.159 --> 00:34:51.040
And we need to start from there and then, you know, go down through like exactly like

00:34:51.040 --> 00:34:56.239
how do we want to improve our business and then try to connect our data scientists, our

00:34:56.239 --> 00:35:02.560
data innovators into those real business decisions or business questions that are there.

00:35:03.280 --> 00:35:08.399
So that's my five-minute Shark Tank pitch on what you need to do.

00:35:08.399 --> 00:35:15.840
You need to align the business so you get them to state their position on data.

00:35:15.840 --> 00:35:19.679
Because otherwise, people like us, we always just like we do our initiatives, we try to

00:35:19.679 --> 00:35:24.479
do our things, and it all hits some glass ceiling at some point, which we're all too

00:35:24.479 --> 00:35:25.040
familiar with.

00:35:25.600 --> 00:35:26.639
Danielle, Anuja?

00:35:26.639 --> 00:35:29.840
I was going to say, I think, you know, one of the things that we had recommended, and

00:35:29.919 --> 00:35:34.959
so we had worked on putting sort of this proposal together, which is very, you know, inclusive

00:35:34.959 --> 00:35:36.239
of what Dan was talking about.

00:35:36.239 --> 00:35:41.280
But I think the first thing was really just actually having an enterprise-wide data strategy

00:35:41.280 --> 00:35:41.919
goal.

00:35:41.919 --> 00:35:47.360
And it's, you know, something on as a goal for our metrics to at least have some traction

00:35:47.360 --> 00:35:49.520
against at that enterprise-wide level.

00:35:50.159 --> 00:35:55.919
One of the anonymous questions from a little bit earlier was, what did you think about

00:35:55.919 --> 00:35:57.679
the like follow through?

00:35:57.679 --> 00:36:01.360
Are you collecting and resharing people's sharings?

00:36:01.360 --> 00:36:03.840
Is there follow through to hold another event?

00:36:03.840 --> 00:36:10.800
We did a couple of things at the end to essentially make people's solutions accessible to all

00:36:10.800 --> 00:36:11.520
of Biogen.

00:36:11.520 --> 00:36:17.600
So just for some context, the finale following all the battle rounds was open invite to everyone.

00:36:17.600 --> 00:36:21.840
And so we had a number of people join from various different departments who weren't

00:36:21.840 --> 00:36:25.679
necessarily participating in the data jam.

00:36:25.679 --> 00:36:31.360
And so one thing we did was collect links to everyone's Power BI's and dashboards and

00:36:31.360 --> 00:36:37.120
shiny applications and kind of final findings and put them in an accessible location for

00:36:37.120 --> 00:36:38.719
everyone to view and see.

00:36:38.719 --> 00:36:43.600
Because again, because it was a five minute shark tank pitch, we couldn't necessarily

00:36:43.600 --> 00:36:44.879
delve into the details.

00:36:44.879 --> 00:36:49.120
And so this gave people the opportunity to look into how people did the analysis and

00:36:49.120 --> 00:36:51.120
what the more detailed findings were.

00:36:51.679 --> 00:36:53.040
So that's one thing that we did.

00:36:54.000 --> 00:36:57.840
We would love to hold another data jam because this one has been so successful.

00:36:57.840 --> 00:37:03.439
We haven't necessarily planned for one yet, but we're, I think, still hoping to do one.

00:37:03.439 --> 00:37:04.800
I mean, what has happened?

00:37:04.800 --> 00:37:05.040
Yeah.

00:37:06.080 --> 00:37:10.320
What has happened is I think Danielle mentioned earlier is people have been coming to with

00:37:10.320 --> 00:37:16.639
us, coming to us with the data sets that have the potential to spin off another data jam.

00:37:16.639 --> 00:37:21.040
And so we're kind of playing with the idea of potentially doing one that's a little more

00:37:21.600 --> 00:37:29.040
maybe hardcore data science for specifically folks who want to dive into the more intense

00:37:29.840 --> 00:37:32.959
data science techniques on a specific data set.

00:37:32.959 --> 00:37:37.679
And so instead of doing a big data jam like we did before, maybe in the interim, we do

00:37:37.679 --> 00:37:39.120
a mini data jam of sorts.

00:37:39.120 --> 00:37:43.280
And so there have been several opportunities to kick something off.

00:37:43.840 --> 00:37:47.120
We just have to kind of get together and decide what that looks like.

00:37:48.080 --> 00:37:51.199
And I think, you know, again, I mentioned our community of practices earlier, so that's

00:37:51.199 --> 00:37:56.320
another avenue that we try to sort of keep this going, the conversation going through.

00:37:56.879 --> 00:38:04.560
We've talked a lot about in these data science Hangouts about data storytelling and communication

00:38:04.560 --> 00:38:09.840
and sometimes like relying that back to having to do your own marketing.

00:38:09.840 --> 00:38:14.879
And I was wondering if you had any marketing lessons learned throughout this process too.

00:38:15.840 --> 00:38:19.520
Although it sounds like you're very successful, you got way more people to sign up than we

00:38:19.520 --> 00:38:20.239
thought we were going to.

00:38:20.959 --> 00:38:23.360
No, the marketing is key.

00:38:23.360 --> 00:38:28.479
So Sam, who's not here today, but she's our marketing expert.

00:38:28.479 --> 00:38:32.639
And I do think marketing makes a big, big difference.

00:38:34.959 --> 00:38:38.000
You know, I think when we sent out, well, we called it a data jam.

00:38:38.000 --> 00:38:38.959
It sounds kind of fun.

00:38:39.520 --> 00:38:44.479
We had a lot of like fun things, like we had like a logo with like a piece of jam on it,

00:38:44.639 --> 00:38:46.080
you know, toast with like jam on it.

00:38:47.040 --> 00:38:50.879
I know it is my jam is the theme.

00:38:50.879 --> 00:38:56.080
I know when we had the finale, the music was jamming by Bob Marley.

00:38:56.080 --> 00:38:57.840
We're coming in, people were walking in.

00:39:00.320 --> 00:39:05.360
And I think when we sent it out, I know we had like a one page flyer to describe this.

00:39:05.360 --> 00:39:10.879
It had very little detail, you know, it said like, you know, work with your colleagues.

00:39:10.879 --> 00:39:13.199
And we really try to say what's in it for them.

00:39:13.439 --> 00:39:14.800
What did they get out of it?

00:39:14.800 --> 00:39:18.800
Instead of like what are really explaining what we're doing, we're just kind of saying,

00:39:18.800 --> 00:39:19.600
you know, what's in there for you.

00:39:19.600 --> 00:39:21.919
Get to meet your colleagues, get to work on something interesting.

00:39:22.879 --> 00:39:25.199
Oh, don't forget the seven C's of jamming.

00:39:25.199 --> 00:39:26.959
Yeah, I don't remember the seven C's.

00:39:28.399 --> 00:39:29.520
Collaboration.

00:39:29.520 --> 00:39:30.719
Creativity, collaboration.

00:39:30.719 --> 00:39:34.800
There's a bunch of C's and the last one we just jokingly called for the seventh C fun.

00:39:36.719 --> 00:39:38.239
We couldn't come up with a seventh one.

00:39:38.239 --> 00:39:41.840
But yeah, I think it was fun for our team too.

00:39:41.840 --> 00:39:46.320
Because like all of us, all four of us love data and love getting people together.

00:39:46.320 --> 00:39:51.040
So we got really kind of creative and crazy with the way that we were pitching it too.

00:39:52.320 --> 00:39:56.080
And so yeah, the logo, for instance, we did a couple of stickers.

00:39:56.080 --> 00:40:04.479
We had kind of swag set up in the office as much as we could and tried to make it make it fun.

00:40:05.199 --> 00:40:09.520
I really like listening to the way that the three of you all like play off each other

00:40:09.520 --> 00:40:12.399
and like answer these questions and go back and forth.

00:40:14.479 --> 00:40:17.760
It just sounds like you did such an amazing job with this event,

00:40:17.760 --> 00:40:21.919
like thinking of all the different parts that make it what it is.

00:40:21.919 --> 00:40:27.280
And I hope that you got the got the recognition internally for this event

00:40:27.280 --> 00:40:29.199
and going like above and beyond to do that.

00:40:29.199 --> 00:40:34.239
And was just curious to learn a little bit more about what that maybe looked like.

00:40:35.280 --> 00:40:38.080
I mean, I think for one thing is our CEO joined

00:40:38.080 --> 00:40:40.239
and he was only planning to join for 20 minutes.

00:40:40.239 --> 00:40:42.560
He ended up staying the full two hours.

00:40:42.560 --> 00:40:44.639
So that was really great.

00:40:44.639 --> 00:40:47.840
And I think, again, there's a lot of positive feedback afterwards.

00:40:50.000 --> 00:40:52.479
And people are looking forward to another one.

00:40:52.479 --> 00:40:55.360
So I think that's the best recognition right there.

00:40:56.320 --> 00:40:56.719
Yeah.

00:40:56.719 --> 00:40:59.120
And I will say for kind of the four of us,

00:40:59.120 --> 00:41:02.320
we kind of organically worked really well together,

00:41:04.000 --> 00:41:06.320
which I don't know how that happened, but I'm glad that it did.

00:41:06.320 --> 00:41:10.879
We each took on the roles that came most naturally to us.

00:41:10.879 --> 00:41:16.479
So, for instance, Sam, she loves putting together graphics and she did marketing.

00:41:16.479 --> 00:41:19.919
And then, you know, someone else would take on the networking piece.

00:41:19.919 --> 00:41:22.560
Someone else would take on the logistics piece.

00:41:22.560 --> 00:41:27.360
And so we each just knew what our role was within the grand scheme of things.

00:41:27.360 --> 00:41:31.520
And that kind of helped us to work really well together from the start.

00:41:31.520 --> 00:41:36.159
So not a lot of conflict in the internal team, which is always good.

00:41:36.719 --> 00:41:39.040
I mean, we were joking if we were like an actual team

00:41:39.040 --> 00:41:41.360
about all the awesome things we could get done.

00:41:43.439 --> 00:41:48.959
So we went heavy on the data jam today and diving into all parts of that.

00:41:48.959 --> 00:41:51.760
But I'm curious to learn a little bit more about

00:41:52.639 --> 00:41:56.320
some of the other things that you're working on as well.

00:41:56.320 --> 00:41:59.439
And like the everyday kind of business problems that you're solving too.

00:42:00.080 --> 00:42:01.120
Oh, boy.

00:42:01.120 --> 00:42:01.439
Okay.

00:42:03.840 --> 00:42:05.120
That sounded like a heavy sight.

00:42:05.120 --> 00:42:06.959
You don't have to answer that.

00:42:06.959 --> 00:42:07.520
It's fine.

00:42:07.520 --> 00:42:08.239
It's complicated.

00:42:09.199 --> 00:42:15.840
A big one that my team is working on is reuse of clinical trial data.

00:42:16.800 --> 00:42:20.719
So clinical trial data is personal information, obviously.

00:42:21.520 --> 00:42:23.520
But it's like protected personal information.

00:42:24.320 --> 00:42:27.040
It's very, very valuable, right?

00:42:27.040 --> 00:42:30.719
I mean, we know, you know, we study diseases that don't have cures.

00:42:30.719 --> 00:42:33.760
We study diseases that don't have medicines.

00:42:34.560 --> 00:42:37.840
We're trying to find better ways to treat the disease,

00:42:37.840 --> 00:42:40.080
trying to find better ways to measure the disease.

00:42:40.080 --> 00:42:44.560
And that's all, you know, held together in this clinical trial data that we run.

00:42:46.000 --> 00:42:50.800
So a big thing that I'm working on right now is how do we best leverage this?

00:42:52.000 --> 00:42:53.919
It is immensely complicated.

00:42:54.639 --> 00:43:02.239
There's many privacy regulations, many GCP, good clinical practice.

00:43:03.760 --> 00:43:05.439
Regulations around this.

00:43:05.439 --> 00:43:13.199
But I have this feeling that we need to find a way to use the data up to its maximum potential

00:43:13.919 --> 00:43:16.879
or maximum allowability and no further.

00:43:17.600 --> 00:43:21.439
But if we don't, if we just say, hey, it's complicated.

00:43:21.439 --> 00:43:22.639
I'm not touching that.

00:43:22.639 --> 00:43:27.199
I feel like we're like losing a big piece of medicinal development.

00:43:28.959 --> 00:43:30.320
So that's a big piece that I'm working on.

00:43:30.320 --> 00:43:32.879
I know Nuja is helping me on that.

00:43:33.760 --> 00:43:35.760
See what they have to say, what they're working on.

00:43:35.760 --> 00:43:36.639
I'm sure it's different.

00:43:37.199 --> 00:43:38.879
So for me, you want to go?

00:43:39.439 --> 00:43:41.040
No, go for it, Danielle.

00:43:41.040 --> 00:43:47.040
So for me specifically, a lot of what I do is really focused on understanding sort of

00:43:48.159 --> 00:43:51.439
the business risk for some of our portfolio and programs.

00:43:51.439 --> 00:43:52.560
So really understanding.

00:43:52.560 --> 00:43:56.080
So what our portfolio looks like, what are the decisions that we're trying to make to

00:43:56.080 --> 00:44:00.639
whether we progress programs or we terminate programs.

00:44:01.280 --> 00:44:05.679
So a lot of it has to do with really modeling and understanding our current portfolio,

00:44:05.679 --> 00:44:08.239
the different decision points, the investment points.

00:44:08.239 --> 00:44:09.040
What's the risk?

00:44:09.040 --> 00:44:09.840
What's the value?

00:44:10.719 --> 00:44:15.760
And ultimately coming up with insights for leadership to then decide leadership and our

00:44:15.760 --> 00:44:19.520
governance, then decide what we what our portfolio should look like.

00:44:20.239 --> 00:44:21.040
What are the programs?

00:44:21.040 --> 00:44:22.320
What are the things that we invest in?

00:44:23.040 --> 00:44:27.520
But again, a lot of this is balancing the business risk with a scientific risk.

00:44:28.399 --> 00:44:31.679
So lots of different like I'm focused a lot more on the operational data

00:44:32.959 --> 00:44:33.600
more than anything.

00:44:33.600 --> 00:44:36.320
But a lot of it is, you know, balancing out those different risks and

00:44:37.679 --> 00:44:41.120
really helping decision makers understand what what the options are.

00:44:41.840 --> 00:44:44.959
So I've been lucky enough to kind of work with several different

00:44:45.679 --> 00:44:47.520
folks within analytics and data sciences.

00:44:47.520 --> 00:44:52.239
So I am helping Dan with part of his secondary use project.

00:44:52.239 --> 00:44:58.479
But I think my biggest project is around automation for our end to end clinical

00:44:58.479 --> 00:45:00.159
reporting and analytics space.

00:45:00.159 --> 00:45:05.840
And so I help to manage, but also contribute to the strategy of understanding, you know,

00:45:06.639 --> 00:45:11.439
what can be automated and also what should be automated, because there is a lot that

00:45:11.439 --> 00:45:15.040
can be automated, but we want to make sure that, you know, the resourcing that we put

00:45:15.040 --> 00:45:19.120
into it is worth the impact that it will eventually drive.

00:45:19.120 --> 00:45:25.040
And so part of that is, you know, playing with the fact that, you know, people work

00:45:25.040 --> 00:45:27.439
in SAS, but how do we bring in additional languages?

00:45:27.439 --> 00:45:30.879
How do we bring in more additional analytics techniques?

00:45:30.879 --> 00:45:32.239
When is it worth doing that?

00:45:32.239 --> 00:45:35.040
And what is the best way logistically to also bring that in?

00:45:35.040 --> 00:45:40.000
So it started off as like a smaller scope of work, but it's kind of ballooned out to

00:45:40.000 --> 00:45:43.679
be this, you know, massive initiative that has been very fun to work on.

00:45:43.679 --> 00:45:46.159
So thank you all for sharing.

00:45:46.159 --> 00:45:46.879
Really interesting.

00:45:47.520 --> 00:45:53.199
I wanted to remind everybody with 10 minutes left here that if I missed any questions from

00:45:53.199 --> 00:45:59.360
anybody in the chat among conversation, feel free to just repost it there or raise your

00:45:59.360 --> 00:46:00.239
hand here too.

00:46:00.800 --> 00:46:07.360
But I know Bill loves this question and we have to ask it too, but was there any application

00:46:07.360 --> 00:46:11.919
of AI or chat GPT or large language models in this?

00:46:12.719 --> 00:46:13.919
Oh, I can take that.

00:46:13.919 --> 00:46:20.879
So we got a lot of questions of, can I take this data and copy and paste it into chat

00:46:20.879 --> 00:46:21.439
GPT?

00:46:22.080 --> 00:46:24.959
Which the answer is no, just FYI.

00:46:24.959 --> 00:46:29.040
If you work at a big company, that answer is no, but we have an internal instance of

00:46:29.040 --> 00:46:31.120
chat GPT that's secure.

00:46:32.399 --> 00:46:34.239
And people did use that.

00:46:34.879 --> 00:46:35.919
We had comments.

00:46:35.919 --> 00:46:39.040
So I think, I forget how many people took the survey, 300 something.

00:46:39.840 --> 00:46:42.080
And people wrote comments in there.

00:46:42.080 --> 00:46:47.280
And so people were doing like sentiment analysis of the comments and trying to pick out some

00:46:47.919 --> 00:46:49.840
insights that were in the comments, which was fun.

00:46:50.719 --> 00:46:51.219
Thank you.

00:46:52.479 --> 00:46:58.239
Anusha, I really like that point you just brought up about, like, we talk about automation

00:46:58.239 --> 00:47:03.439
a lot, but when is it worth going through the process of doing the automation and using

00:47:03.439 --> 00:47:04.399
resources to do that?

00:47:04.399 --> 00:47:08.159
And I'm curious, like, how do you figure that out?

00:47:09.280 --> 00:47:10.560
I mean, that's tough, right?

00:47:10.560 --> 00:47:17.919
Because you have an initial estimate of, yeah, I'll be able to develop the macros or the

00:47:17.919 --> 00:47:20.879
scripts needed to be able to automate this the next amount of time.

00:47:20.879 --> 00:47:25.040
But then there's other pieces that we need to factor in around, you know, how long is

00:47:25.040 --> 00:47:26.239
it going to take to adopt?

00:47:26.239 --> 00:47:27.760
How long is it going to take to scale?

00:47:29.040 --> 00:47:31.760
And then there's a learning curve associated with it as well.

00:47:31.760 --> 00:47:38.159
So it is, that's something we've been, as more people become aware of the automation

00:47:38.159 --> 00:47:42.080
initiative, it's automatically leading to more ideas flowing in.

00:47:42.080 --> 00:47:47.520
And so we're really having to put a structure in place to try and gauge from the very beginning

00:47:47.520 --> 00:47:51.760
how much resourcing is going to be used in order to make this.

00:47:51.760 --> 00:47:56.719
And so I know that doesn't really answer your question, but that's because, you know, it's

00:47:56.719 --> 00:48:01.120
tough to gauge right from the very beginning how much resourcing is going to be put in.

00:48:01.840 --> 00:48:09.199
But we do try to account for both, you know, development in addition to change management,

00:48:09.199 --> 00:48:16.320
in addition to adoption and set kind of tangible and achievable targets intermittently.

00:48:16.320 --> 00:48:19.840
Yeah, I was going to say, cue up the XKCD, but I see someone already put it in there.

00:48:19.840 --> 00:48:23.520
I saw someone put that in chat, and I was like, it's got to be the one that I think

00:48:23.520 --> 00:48:24.080
it is.

00:48:25.840 --> 00:48:27.199
That's a good one for us to all take down.

00:48:28.159 --> 00:48:31.120
I remember that one, and I didn't know where to find it.

00:48:33.840 --> 00:48:38.159
Nessa, I see you had a follow-up question from the previous question.

00:48:38.159 --> 00:48:39.679
You want to jump in here?

00:48:39.679 --> 00:48:45.439
Yeah, I just wanted to ask about the internal instance of chat GPT you're dealing with,

00:48:45.439 --> 00:48:50.479
because, well, I've been talking to a bunch of other companies I'm really interested in

00:48:51.760 --> 00:48:53.600
how people are doing this.

00:48:53.600 --> 00:48:56.159
Is it a web chat tool with a GUI?

00:48:56.239 --> 00:49:03.439
Like, most people access chat GPT in the real world, or is it all API based?

00:49:05.199 --> 00:49:08.399
And also, is it accessible to people who are not data scientists?

00:49:08.399 --> 00:49:11.919
Like, can a chemist access this really easily?

00:49:13.120 --> 00:49:14.800
I don't know much about it.

00:49:14.800 --> 00:49:19.600
I feel like when I saw it, it was command line, so I would not call that a GUI.

00:49:20.399 --> 00:49:26.320
But I think it's like a private Azure instance of the GPT.

00:49:27.040 --> 00:49:29.040
But I don't know too much.

00:49:29.040 --> 00:49:35.280
But no, I don't think we don't have like a chat GPT for Biogen, where it's like

00:49:36.080 --> 00:49:38.080
friendly user interface and ask it any question.

00:49:38.080 --> 00:49:38.879
We don't have that yet.

00:49:42.239 --> 00:49:45.360
Yeah, thank you all for the great questions.

00:49:45.600 --> 00:49:50.800
Alan, you had a follow up question around more of the broader community events.

00:49:50.800 --> 00:49:51.439
Want to jump in?

00:49:52.000 --> 00:49:55.040
Yeah, I'm just curious if there are other kind of things that connect

00:49:56.159 --> 00:50:01.760
into like a single sort of community of practice for folks who participated in the jam,

00:50:01.760 --> 00:50:04.560
but also more broadly, do you have other events?

00:50:05.120 --> 00:50:07.679
Is there other kind of conscientious organizing going on?

00:50:08.560 --> 00:50:11.919
Just curious what that looks like to kind of keep these folks

00:50:12.639 --> 00:50:17.040
seeing one another and potentially connecting, you know, beyond that event.

00:50:17.840 --> 00:50:20.159
Yeah, I can speak for the community of practice that we run.

00:50:20.159 --> 00:50:21.520
So we try to have forums.

00:50:22.479 --> 00:50:24.560
But we're trying to have it, you know, at least every other month.

00:50:24.560 --> 00:50:27.679
And so there's a series that we have called data bites.

00:50:27.679 --> 00:50:31.760
And basically, what it is, is either bringing somebody from it or somebody from the community

00:50:31.760 --> 00:50:34.000
to talk about the work that they're doing.

00:50:34.879 --> 00:50:40.320
And or more recently, we had one that was actually somebody that participated in data jam

00:50:40.320 --> 00:50:44.879
and wanted to leverage the data jam network to look at their data and help generate insights.

00:50:45.919 --> 00:50:50.800
And I know we've also talked about doing some more collective

00:50:51.840 --> 00:50:53.600
meetings across the different communities.

00:50:53.600 --> 00:50:55.840
So kind of gathering all the different communities together

00:50:55.840 --> 00:50:59.600
on a more regular basis, did bring a lot of those communities together.

00:51:00.639 --> 00:51:04.639
And so there are definitely plans to start to continue that.

00:51:04.639 --> 00:51:06.479
It's been a little bit hectic at Biogen lately.

00:51:06.479 --> 00:51:08.560
So we haven't been able to do as much as we wanted to.

00:51:08.560 --> 00:51:11.840
But I think now that things are somewhat settling,

00:51:11.840 --> 00:51:15.280
we are definitely looking at sort of the next few key events.

00:51:16.080 --> 00:51:16.719
Well, thanks.

00:51:16.719 --> 00:51:18.560
I hope those are successful.

00:51:18.560 --> 00:51:20.159
Sounds like a good, a really good foundation.

00:51:20.879 --> 00:51:24.479
Bill, I see you had a question around their environment.

00:51:24.479 --> 00:51:25.199
You want to jump in?

00:51:26.080 --> 00:51:31.040
And the question was around different cloud providers.

00:51:31.040 --> 00:51:35.679
Are you heavy into Azure or AWS one over the other?

00:51:35.679 --> 00:51:39.439
Or do you have mostly on-prem, data versus cloud?

00:51:40.719 --> 00:51:45.280
And as always, no worries if these are certain questions that you can't answer too.

00:51:46.560 --> 00:51:48.239
I'm pretty sure I have a little bit of everything.

00:51:50.639 --> 00:51:51.360
That's a good answer.

00:51:52.719 --> 00:51:57.280
So we'll check here to see if there were any questions that we missed.

00:51:58.719 --> 00:52:02.959
But something I was curious about when you were talking about the different community events

00:52:02.959 --> 00:52:07.040
and people who maybe are new to data science as well,

00:52:08.399 --> 00:52:11.600
what does the training look like for your team?

00:52:11.600 --> 00:52:15.760
So if somebody maybe, I guess there's two factors here,

00:52:15.760 --> 00:52:20.879
like onboarding for someone who comes in with data science experience or analytics experience

00:52:20.879 --> 00:52:26.159
versus also somebody who maybe hadn't used data and science before, but wants to.

00:52:26.159 --> 00:52:26.879
Maybe Danielle?

00:52:29.199 --> 00:52:31.199
A lot of it really is on-the-job training.

00:52:31.760 --> 00:52:35.919
So it's really just once you, you know, working with the team, working with your manager.

00:52:36.800 --> 00:52:40.800
But at the same time too, I know for some of what we hire for it,

00:52:40.800 --> 00:52:42.800
we try to sort of be a little bit diverse.

00:52:42.800 --> 00:52:47.360
So a lot of times there are some technical aspects that we are looking for.

00:52:47.360 --> 00:52:51.439
But a lot of the times for anything really data related in my world,

00:52:51.439 --> 00:52:55.760
I look for people that are just genuinely curious and want to solve problems.

00:52:55.760 --> 00:53:00.800
So I feel like as long as you have those two skills and that you're willing to learn,

00:53:00.800 --> 00:53:04.479
that's pretty much how we get things done.

00:53:05.040 --> 00:53:07.199
I don't know, Dan, in your space, if it's any different,

00:53:07.199 --> 00:53:09.919
but that's at least how I sort of handle things over here.

00:53:10.800 --> 00:53:14.959
Yeah, I think in the data science groups, we hire a lot of more senior people.

00:53:15.760 --> 00:53:17.919
There's not like a lot of entry-level roles there.

00:53:18.479 --> 00:53:22.399
But I think maybe you're also hinting at like a, although I hate the word,

00:53:22.399 --> 00:53:26.239
a data literacy kind of effort of how do you,

00:53:26.239 --> 00:53:32.000
how does every single person in the entire organization know not to present a pie chart?

00:53:33.439 --> 00:53:34.719
You know, and stuff like that.

00:53:34.719 --> 00:53:36.560
And that's something that we need to look at.

00:53:36.560 --> 00:53:38.479
And I think these community of practices that we have

00:53:38.479 --> 00:53:40.320
are the best way that we can really do it.

00:53:40.320 --> 00:53:41.199
It's organic.

00:53:41.199 --> 00:53:45.760
It's leaning on people already wanting to learn

00:53:45.760 --> 00:53:49.120
and then like kind of helping them get up to the next level

00:53:49.120 --> 00:53:50.959
with what they already want to learn.

00:53:50.959 --> 00:53:54.080
I know kind of speaking to the communities of practice,

00:53:54.080 --> 00:53:56.639
but there are some like ours are a little more general,

00:53:56.639 --> 00:53:57.919
but there are specialized ones.

00:53:57.919 --> 00:54:02.800
So there's a machine learning group that dives into that a little bit more.

00:54:02.800 --> 00:54:06.399
And we're about to start a data science conference,

00:54:07.280 --> 00:54:13.760
which will bring in kind of speakers and such for people to learn a little bit more there.

00:54:15.679 --> 00:54:16.639
Thank you so much.

00:54:18.000 --> 00:54:21.600
I feel like I just have to say this because Biogen's in Boston,

00:54:21.600 --> 00:54:25.439
but I run the Boston News Hour group with my co-host Kevin.

00:54:25.439 --> 00:54:29.360
And if anybody from the team would be interested in joining us,

00:54:29.360 --> 00:54:32.399
I just shared the link to our event in the chat.

00:54:32.399 --> 00:54:36.080
But we have a series of lightning talks coming up

00:54:36.080 --> 00:54:39.840
and it'd be cool to do some events with some others from Biogen too.

00:54:41.919 --> 00:54:47.040
Let me double check here on any questions we missed.

00:54:47.040 --> 00:54:50.639
If anybody in the last minute here wants to raise your hand.

00:54:51.600 --> 00:54:52.159
Feel free.

